  37  }
```

In this example, `parts.size()` is equal to `4`, which means it will enter the `else if` block. This is the block for parsing the legacy topic names, as `line 28` mentions

Then lines `29-32` get run (translations included):
```java
   // parts = ["my-tenant", "my-ns", "topic", "with/slashes"];

      ...
  29  this.tenant = parts.get(0);
   // this.tenant = "my-tenant";        // Good
  30  this.cluster = parts.get(1);
   // this.cluster = "my-ns";           // **BAD**
  31  this.namespacePortion = parts.get(2);
   // this.namespacePortion = "topic";  // **BAD**
  32  this.localName = parts.get(3);
   // this.localName = "with/slashes";  // **BAD**

```

**Expected behavior**
The expected behavior is that it should parse the tenant, cluster, namespace and topic-name correctly.

The code should not enter the `else if` condition. It should enter the `if` condition. 
This line assumes that the topic will not have any slashes in it. But this assumption is incorrect. The [documentation](http://pulsar.apache.org/docs/en/concepts-messaging/#topics) explicitly states that "topic names are freeform". It's also mentioned on line 14-15 in the comments.The Java [code](https://github.com/apache/pulsar/blob/639fbf1801b227bb191cfc548f26906902481b8f/pulsar-common/src/test/java/org/apache/pulsar/common/naming/TopicNameTest.java#L180) tests for this case (which makes me think perhaps the tests are broken as well? I'm not sure what's going on)

This seems like it would be better suited to using a regex to parse the completeTopicString. 


